A lot of financial scams have=C2=A0the form of =E2=80=9Caffinity fraud,=E2=
=80=9D where a fraudster offers fake investments, pays Ponzi-like returns a=
nd =E2=80=9Cexploits the trust and friendship that exist in groups of peopl=
e who have something in common.=E2=80=9D Often the targets are members of s=
ome ethnic or religious group, who are more likely to trust one of their ow=
n with their money, but all sorts of common bonds can work. The more intens=
e the sense of intra-group connection and trust, the more effective the sca=
m is. We talked a few months ago about a Harvard Business School alumnus wh=
o allegedly targeted fellow Harvard MBAs for a Ponzi scheme. In some sense,=
 running a Ponzi scheme on your classmates is the worst possible use of a H=
arvard MBA, but also I kind of admire it: That=E2=80=99s an affinity group =
with a lot of trust and loyalty and also a lot of money!Anyway here=E2=80=
=99s a Wall Street Journal article about=C2=A0what I assume is the first al=
leged pickleball affinity fraud, but not the last:Rodney =E2=80=9CRocket=E2=
=80=9D Grubbs =E2=80=A6 was well-known and well-liked in Brookville =E2=80=
=94 a town of 2,600 tucked amid rolling hills about 40 miles northwest of C=
incinnati =E2=80=94 where he coached tennis and opened a pickleball shop. H=
e traveled to dozens of tournaments a year, playing and selling merchandise=
 through a company, Pickleball Rocks, that he touted as =E2=80=9Cthe world=
=E2=80=99s most recognized pickleball apparel brand.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But auth=
orities say he was also issuing promissory notes =E2=80=94 usually for $25,=
000 at 12% interest over 18 months=E2=80=94to people across the country, te=
lling them they were part of a small group of investors and seldom making g=
ood. In court filings, Grubbs said he owes a total of $47.5 million, includ=
ing interest. The money has largely vanished. ...Grubbs=E2=80=99s creditors=
 lament that they were vulnerable to manipulation by someone they knew and =
trusted. The affair has entangled the reigning senior national pickleball c=
hampion, droves of retirees and a priest.=C2=A0He =E2=80=9Chasn=E2=80=99t b=
een charged with a crime=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chas said he never issued a l=
oan he didn=E2=80=99t intend to repay,=E2=80=9D but one alleged victim star=
ted =E2=80=9Ca Facebook group called =E2=80=98From Pickleball Rocks to Pris=
on Rocks.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Another now plays pickleball =E2=80=9Cwearing a=
 Pickleball Rocks T-shirt with the word =E2=80=98Rocks=E2=80=99 covered up.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhy would he take advantage of an 87-year-old friend,=E2=
